item.text: If the client has no acute medical or psychiatric issues that could require immediate clinical attention – for example being intoxicated, confused, disorganized thinking, unable to communicate or sit down for a period, looks very medically ill – then proceed.
Tip

The Mental Wellness Tool aims to catch as many people with mental health problems as possible, even if it means that there might be some people who in the end don’t have the disorder that they screened positive for (false positives). This approach reduces the chance of missing anyone who has mental health problems.
I would like to ask you a few questions so we can figure out together what you are dealing with. The following 3 questions ask about your experience in the past two weeks.
Tip

Tip #1
The Mental Wellness Tool (mwTool) is a brief survey that screens for severe mental disorders (including psychosis and mania), common mental disorders (including depression, anxiety, and post-traumatic disorder), alcohol use disorders, and suicide risk.

Tip #2
Note that the Mental Wellness Tool is a screening tool, so its results are not diagnostic. Use the tool to better understand the client's problems and determine next steps, but do not provide definite diagnoses (e.g., "you are diagnosed with alcohol use disorder").
In the last 2 weeks, how often have you been feeling down, depressed, or hopeless?
In the last 2 weeks, how often have you been feeling nervous, anxious, or on edge?
In the last 2 weeks, how often have you been so restless that it's hard to sit still?
The client's Mental Wellness Tool results:
The client shows no signs of any mental health problems
Supervisor recommendation form (for incomplete answers)
Tip

Based on the determination of the supervisor, either:
  •  Go back and fill out the Mental Wellness Tool questions which have incomplete answers or;
  •  Write down what the supervisor recommended for this client or the reasons for terminating the session, and end the screening process.
Since responses are incomplete, please contact your supervisor.
Please describe what the supervisor recommended
In the past year, how often do you have a drink containing alcohol?

In the past year, how many drinks containing alcohol do you have on a typical day when you are drinking?

By a 'standard drink' I mean a bottle or can of beer, a small glass of wine, a shot or a small cocktail.
In the past year, how many times have you used a recreational drug or used a prescription medication for non-medical reasons?

In the past year, have you ever felt that your thoughts were being directly interfered with or controlled by some outside force or person in a way that many people would find hard to believe (for instance, through telepathy)?
In the past year, have there been times when you felt that a group of people was plotting to cause you serious harm or injury?
In the past year, have there been times when you felt that something so strange was going on that other people would find it very hard to believe?
In the past year, did you at any time hear voices saying quite a few words or sentences when there was no one around that might account for it?
In the past month, have you wished you were dead or wished you could go to sleep and not wake up?
In the past month, have you had any actual thoughts of killing yourself?
In the past 3 months, have you ever done anything, started to do anything, or prepared to do anything to end your life?

Tip

Based on the determination of the supervisor, either:
  •  Go back and fill out the Mental Wellness Tool questions which have incomplete answers or;
  •  Write down what the supervisor recommended for this client or the reasons for terminating the session, and end the screening process.
